a.com/biography/Frederick-IV-king-of-Denmark-and-Norway |website=Encyclopedia Britannica |accessdate=18 November 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n* [[List of Prime Ministers of Denmark#List of Grand Chancellors (1699\u20131730)|Grand Chancellor]] &ndash; [[Ulrik Adolf Holstein]]\n\n==Events==\n\n===Undated===\n* [[Store Kongensgade Faience Manufactury]] opens in Copenhagen with a monopoly on production of fajance with blue decorations.<ref name=DSD>{{cite web|url=http://denstoredanske.dk/Kunst_og_kultur/Kunsth\u00e5ndv\u00e6rk_og_design/Keramik_(porcel\u00e6n,_fajance,_stent\u00f8j,_lert\u00f8j)/Store_Kongensgade_Fajancefabrik|title=Store Kongensgade Fajancefabrik|language=Danish|website=denstoredanske.dk|accessdate=27  March 2018}}</ref>\n* The ''[[Lille Gr\u00f8nnegade Theatre]]'' in Copenhagen, the first public theater in Denmark, is opened. <ref>[http://www.kvinfo.dk/side/597/bio/1451/origin/170/ Dansk kvindebiografisk leksikon]</ref>]]\n\n==Births==\n* 2 September &mdash; [[Vigilius Eriksen]], painter (died [[1782 in Denmark|1782]])\n\n==Deaths==\n\n===Full date unknown===\n* [[Beno\u00eet Le Coffre]], painter to the Danish Court (born [[1671 in Denmark|1671]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Denmark year nav}}\n{{Year in Europe|1722}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1722 In Denmark}}\n[[Category:1722 in Denmark| ]]\n[[Category:1720s in Denmark]]\n[[Category:1722 by country|Denmark]]\n[[Category:Years of the 18th century in Denmark]]\n", "name_user": "Jcoolbro", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 -WP:WCWproject (Square brackets without correct beginning)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1722_in_Denmark"}
{"title_page": "Energy Murambadoro", "text_new": "{{short description|Zimbabwean footballer}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Energy Murambadoro\n| image =\n| fullname = Energy Murambadoro\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1982|06|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Gweru]], Zimbabwe\n| currentclub  = [[AmaZulu F.C.]]\n| clubnumber = 1\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 =\n| youthclubs1 =\n| years1 = 2003 | years2 = 2003\u20132004 | years3 = 2004\u20132005 | years4 = 2005\u20132006 | years5 = 2006 | years6 = 2007 | years7 = 2008\u20132012 | years8 = 2010 | years9 = 2013\u2013\n| clubs1 = [[CAPS United]] | clubs2 = [[Hellenic FC|Hellenic]] | clubs3 = [[Hapoel Bnei Sakhnin FC|Bnei Sakhnin]] | clubs4 = [[CAPS United]] | clubs5 = [[Benoni Premier United]] | clubs6 = [[CAPS United]] | clubs7 = [[Bidvest Wits F.C.|Bidvest Wits]] | clubs8 = \u2192 [[Mpumalanga Black Aces]] (loan) | clubs9 = [[AmaZulu F.C.]] | caps1 =  | goals1 =  | caps2 = 10 | goals2 = 0 | caps3 = 9 | goals3 = 0 | caps4 =  | goals4 =  | caps5 = 2 | goals5 = 0 | caps6 =  | goals6 =  | caps7 = 27 | goals7 = 0 | caps8 = 5 | goals8 = 0 | caps9 = 0 |goals9 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2002\u20132008\n| nationalteam1 = [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 27\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 16 June 2011\n| ntupdate = 16 June 2011\n}}\n\n'''Energy Murambadoro''' (nickname \"Gokwe\"<ref name=pindula>{{Cite web|url=https://pindula.co.zw/Energy_Murambadoro|title=Energy Murambadoro - Pindula|website=pindula.co.zw|access-date=2019-05-07}}</ref>: born 27 June 1982 in [[Gweru]]) is a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[football (soccer)]] [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]]<ref name=pindula /> who plays for [[AmaZulu F.C.]] in the South African [[Premier Soccer League]]. He has retired from international football with [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]]. He has two children.<ref name=pindula />\n\n==Club career==\nOn 24 November 2009 [[Mpumalanga Black Aces F.C.]] bolstered their goalkeeping department with the acquisition of Murambadoro.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1659/south-africa/2009/11/24/1644171/goalkeeper-energy-murambadoro-joins-mpumalanga-black-aces|title=Goalkeeper Energy Murambadoro Joins Mpumalanga Black Aces {{!}} Goal.com|website=www.goal.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-21}}</ref> On 20 October 2012, he was one of sixteen players who were cleared of match fixing by the Zimbabwe Football Association.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thezimbabwean.co.uk/sport/football/61650/sunday-chidzambwa-rushwaya-get-life.html |title=Sunday Chidzambwa, Rushwaya get life bans |date=20 October 2012 |author=Moses Chibaye |publisher=The Zimbabwean |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105161034/http://www.thezimbabwean.co.uk/sport/football/61650/sunday-chidzambwa-rushwaya-get-life.html |archivedate=5 November 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe following are the clubs that Energy played including the years and transfers: \n\nIn 2003/2004 Energy left Caps United (Zimbabwe) and Joined Hellenics (South Africa)\n\nIn 2004/2005 Energy left Hellenics (South Africa) and Joined Bnei Sakhnin (Israel)\n\nIn 2005/2006 Energy left Joined Bnei Sakhnin (Israel) and Joined Caps United (Zimbabwe)\n\nIn 2006/2007 Energy left Caps United (Zimbabwe) and Joined  Hellenics (South Africa)\n\nIn 2007/2008 Energy left Hellenics (South Africa) and Joined  Caps United (Zimbabwe)\n\nIn 2008/2009 Energy left Caps United (Zimbabwe) and Joined  Bidvest Wits FC (South Africa)\n\nIn 2009/2010 Energy left Bidvest Wits FC (South Africa) and Joined Black Ace (South Africa)\n\nIn 2009/2010 Energy left Black Ace (South Africa) and Joined Bidvest Wits FC (South Africa)\n\nIn 2012/2013 Energy left Bidvest Wits FC (South Africa) and from there he had no club.\n\nIn 2014/2015 Energy joined Black Ace (South Africa)<br />In 2014/2015 Energy left Black Ace (South Africa) and AmaZulu FC (South Africa)\n\nIn 2014/2015 Energy left AmaZulu FC (South Africa) and Black Ace (South Africa)\n\nIn 2015/2016 Energy left Black Ace (South Africa) and AmaZulu FC (South Africa)\n\n==International career==\nHe was a member of the Zimbabwean [[2004 African Nations Cup]] team, who finished bottom of their group in the first round of competition, thus failing to secure qualification for the quarter-finals. He also participated at the [[2006 African Nations Cup]], with the same outcome.\nFamous Zimbabwe coach Sir Derek Nicholls regarded Energy as the best goalkeeper the nation has ever seen and nicknamed him Pat in goal.{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{NFT player|pid=7401}}\n\n{{Zimbabwe squad 2004 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n{{Zimbabwe squad 2006 Africa Cup of Nations}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murambadoro, Energy}}\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Gweru]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwe international footballers]]\n[[Category:Bnei Sakhnin F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Israel]]\n[[Category:Expatriate soccer players in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Bidvest Wits F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean expatriate sportspeople in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Mpumalanga Black Aces F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Hellenic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:CAPS United players]]\n[[Category:2004 African Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:2006 Africa Cup of Nations players]]\n[[Category:Israeli Premier League players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n\n\n{{Zimbabwe-footy-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Energy Murambadoro\n| image =\n| fullname = Energy Murambadoro\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1982|06|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Gweru]], Zimbabwe\n| curren